<HEADLINE>
FT  16 APR 93 / Letter: GEC is also on British Rail's track
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr DOUGLAS GADD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, In his letter, 'BR should use leasing finance to buy British' (April
13), Mr Hugh Bayley MP says that ABB is the only British company that has
the ability to produce modern aluminium bodied railway carriages.
This is incorrect. GEC Alsthom is currently building aluminium bodied trains
for British Rail. These trains are being supplied to Network SouthEast where
priority is being given to replacing old rolling stock.
GEC Alsthom does not itself manufacture aluminium body shells, which
represent only about 10 per cent of the cost of the trains, preferring to
source these from outside suppliers, including ABB's factory located in Mr
Bayley's York constituency.
If GEC Alsthom secures orders for either InterCity or Network SouthEast
trains, ABB will be given the opportunity to compete for the supply of body
shells and other equipment.
On the other hand, if British Rail asks ABB to supply new trains, GEC
Alsthom will offer to supply traction drives and power supplies which ABB
does not manufacture in the UK.
Like Mr Bayley, I am hopeful that British Rail will soon be allowed to
acquire new rolling stock to help underpin the future of the British Rail
transportation manufacturing industry.
Douglas Gadd,
GEC Alsthom,
PO Box 70,
Mill Road,
Rugby,
Warwickshire
</TEXT>
<XX>
